<Link id="l00475" /><CodeLine lineNumber="475"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// facts.  Note that this method is not suitable for merging facts along</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00476" /><CodeLine lineNumber="476"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// different paths in a CFG; that&#39;s what the mergeIn function is for.  This</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00477" /><CodeLine lineNumber="477"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// is for merging facts gathered about the same value at the same location</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00478" /><CodeLine lineNumber="478"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// through two independent means.</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00479" /><CodeLine lineNumber="479"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// Notes:</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00480" /><CodeLine lineNumber="480"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// &#42; This method does not promise to return the most precise possible lattice</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00481" /><CodeLine lineNumber="481"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   value implied by A and B.  It is allowed to return any lattice element</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00482" /><CodeLine lineNumber="482"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   which is at least as strong as &#42;either&#42; A or B (unless our facts</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00483" /><CodeLine lineNumber="483"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  ///   conflict, see below).</span></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00484" /><CodeLine lineNumber="484"><span class="doxyHighlightComment">  /// &#42; Due to unreachable code, the intersection of two lattice values could be</span></CodeLine>
